<br>
1. Undead of all types only have proximity aggro<br>
<br>
The example cited as against decaying skeletons, which in most areas (with the exception of Nektulos and Kunark) aren't KOS to anyone, thus proximity aggro doesn't work on them.  Taunt sure does though, you can make one hit you by pressing the taunt button until successful.   <br>
<br>
Also, there are MANY examples of undead who simply ignore range aggro... it cannot be said that they're &quot;like they're rooted&quot;, otherwise the concept of gimping Arch Lich Rhag Zhadune by using a SK to build up huge amounts of aggro and backing out of melee range to avoid being hit wouldn't be in-game, but it is.   I tend to think that undead pay greater weight to proximity, but it's not the only fact like a rooted mob.<br>
<br>
<br>
2. Disarm doesn't add hate<br>
<br>
Disarm ALWAYS adds hate, Disarm is actually the most reliable aggro &quot;generation&quot; tool that we have (something which adds numerical hate) aside from melee damage.   <br>
A fail or success on disarm is irrelevant, a non-kos mob will ALWAYS try to kill you if you are near it and press disarm.   <br>
<br>
3. Turning off attack and hitting &quot;beg&quot; helps with aggro<br>
<br>
Beg doesn't cause hate on any mob which isnt' coded to react violently to a &quot;low failure&quot;... what I mean by this is beg has multiple options on a roll.  Either 1. You will receive something.. success.. 2. You will be ignored or 3. You will be attacked.  It's possible that there are also differnet levels of &quot;success&quot; as well, in terms of amount received and even in some rare instances, experience.  I haven't seen this since I don't waste much time begging, but it's a possibility.  Any mob NOT coded &quot;to be begged from&quot; will not react to beg whatsoever, so turning off attack to beg is counterproductive, as it will result in less generated aggro.<br>
<br>
